title: Alpha Particle Induced Fission of 209Bi at 55.7 and 58.6 MeV

x4freetext: Alpha Particle Induced Fission of 209Bi at 55.7 and
58.6 MeV
Old name = S.S.Rattan, New name = Sarbjit Singh
ABSTRACT: Alpha particle induced fission studies of
209Bi have been carried out at alpha particle energies
of 55.7 MeV and 58.6 MeV using gamma ray spectrometry.
Cross sections for the production of fission products
have been determined. Mass distributions have been
found to be broad with a peak near mass 104.
Charge distribution in the alpha particle induced
fission of 209Bi has been studied at alpha particle
energies of 55.7 MeV and 58.6 MeV. Fractional
cumulative yields of 97-Zr, 99-Mo, 101-Mo, 112-Pd and
117m-Cd have been determined using gamma ray
spectrometry. Width of charge distribution has been
found to be broad.

x4codes.hlp: Bhabha Atomic Research Centre, Trombay, Mumbai, India

x4freetext: Targets of Super Pure 209-Bi were prepared by vacuum
evaporation on 25.4 Mumeter Super Pure Aluminium
Foil.  Targets of 2 mg/cm**2 of Bismuth were used
for Irradiation.  In order to avoid the cross
contamination of fission products due to large activity
of direct reaction products, the 209-Bi Target was
Covered with a 0.76 mumeter super pure aluminium foil.
This will allow the fission products to pass and will
prevent the reaction products.  The whole assembly was
put in a target holder and irradiated for a suitable
length of time with a 60 MeV Alpha Particle Beam of ~ 1
Micro-Ampere.  The incident alpha energy on the first
bismuth target was 58.6 MeV Where as on the second
bismuth target it was 55.7 MeV.
Bismuth targets and aluminium catchers were
separated from each other carefully to avoid cross
contamination. Aluminium catchers were mounted
separately on perspex plates in suitable geometry.

x4codes.hlp: Variable Energy Cyclotron Centre, Kolkata, India

x4freetext: Three Irradiations were Carried Out For
60, 60 and 15 Minutes.
In Each Irradiation the Decay of the Gamma Ray
Peak of the Fission Products were Followed For Suitable
Lenth of Time
The errors listed are the standard deviations
between the results from different irradiations and
various gamma rays
Data taken from  p.170 of main reference.
